\section{Philosopher}
\label{philosopher}
\newcommand{\imply}{$\Rightarrow$}
d5 6
a10 4
discarding many popular misconceptions.  They are, in many ways, the
encyclopedias and expert opinions of the medieval world.  Philosophers
are also well versed in using the unusual and obscure indexing methods
employed in medieval libraries.
d12 1
a12 1
\subsection{Restrictions}
d14 16
a29 1
\subsubsection{Language Restriction}
d37 1
a37 1
times 10 books, written in languages they are literate in.
d39 1
a39 1
\subsection{Definitions}
d41 3
a43 4
The Philosopher Profession is designed as a hierarchical structure,
with several separate Realms of knowledge, each of which has its own
Major Fields.  Major Fields, in turn, possess Minor Fields, and these
possess Sub-Fields.
d51 1
a51 1
\subsubsection{Major Fields}
d53 11
a63 22
Realms are divided into large blocks of knowledge, called Major
Fields.  GMs should not need to add new Major Fields to the Realms,
but may do so if they wish.

\subsubsection{Minor Fields}

Small, and quite specific divisions of a Major Field, these are not
limited to only those suggested below.  A.  Philosopher may learn
almost any sub-division of a Major Field as a Minor Field, with the GM
as the final arbiter.  Minor Fields should not be too specific, and
they may contain several possible Sub-Fields.  The most common Minor
Fields concern a particular race or area pertaining to the Major Field.

\subsubsection{Sub-Fields}

These are the smallest and most specific division of knowledge within
the Philosopher Profession.  A Philosopher may learn almost any small
division of a Minor Field as a Sub-Field.  The most common Sub-Fields
are: Type or Race within an Area, history as pertaining to a
particular Race or Area, Colleges within Branches, Individuals within
Factions or Groups (Powers, Demi-Powers, Dragons), and within the
Animal and Plant Worlds, specific subgroups within types.
d65 1
a65 13
\begin{example}
Magical World \imply Undead \imply Greater \imply Vampires, or Magical
World \imply Undead \imply Undead in the Baronies \imply Greater Undead in the
baronies.

Magical World \imply History \& Theory \imply Thaumaturgies \imply
Illusion.  or Magical World \imply History \& Theory \imply Backfires
\imply Backfires in the Thaumaturgical Colleges.

Animal World \imply Avians \imply Nocturnal Birds \imply Owls, or
Animal World \imply Avians \imply The Birds of Alfheim \imply Nocturnal Birds
of Alfheim.
\end{example}
d67 6
a72 35
\subsubsection{Parent Field}

The Field (or Realm) in the hierarchy above the Field concerned is
referred to as the Field's Parent.  The Parent of a Minor Field or
Sub-Field is the next Field up in the hierarchy; the Parent of a Major
Field is its Realm.

\begin{example}
Parent of the Major Field ``Heraldry \& Genealogy'' is the Realm
``The Social World''.
\end{example}

\subsubsection{Child Field}

Any Fields in the hierarchy that derive from the Field (or Realm)
concerned are referred to as Child Fields.

\begin{example}
Minor Fields ``Colours'', ``Metals'', and ``Furs'' are Child Fields of
Major Field ``Heraldry \& Genealogy''.
\end{example}

\subsubsection{Library}

Any place with 50 or more books may be considered a library, for the
purposes of study.  Libraries are rated for the number of days that a
Philosopher may study in them to answer any particular question.  This
rating is usually equal to Books divided by 50.  Some libraries with
specific collections may be rated higher for some Realms than others.

\begin{example}
The library of the Mittelmark University of Magical Sciences has many
more books dealing with Magic than any other Realm. It is rated at 10
days normally or 15 days if the question is in the Magical World.
\end{example}
d74 1
a74 6
GMs should bear in mind that the books in some libraries will be
predominately in particular languages, and that if the Philosopher is
not literate in that language, or languages, the library may be of
reduced usefulness.

\subsection{Structure}
d81 21
a101 3
at any or all of Ranks 4, 7, and 10, the Philosopher wishes to forego
learning another Realm, they receive an extra 8 Points to spend on
Fields.
d103 1
a103 1
\subsubsection{Fields}
d105 3
a107 6
At each Rank above 0 (including 4, 7, and 10), the
Philosopher receives a number of Points to spend on Major, Minor and
Sub-Fields.  The number of Points received is: at Ranks 1 to 4, 3; at
Ranks 5 to 7, 5; and at Ranks 8 to 10, 7.  The Points costs are: Major
Field, 3; Minor Field, 2; Sub-Field, 1.  Unspent Points are retained
and may be used together with the Points received for further Ranks.
d109 1
a109 1
\subsubsection{Field Restrictions}
d111 5
a115 2
A Philosopher may never learn a field that they do not possess the
Parent of.
d117 1
a117 7
\begin{example}
A Philosopher may not learn the Sub-Field ``Carzalan Heraldry'',
unless they already know Minor Field ``Heraldry of the Baronies'',
which in turn they could not possess without the Major Field
``Heraldry \& Genealogy'', and ultimately the Realm ``The Social
World''.
\end{example}
d119 5
a123 3
These requirements are pre-requisites, not co-requisites.  Therefore a
Sub-field may not be learnt at the same Rank as the Minor Field that
is its Parent.
d125 23
a147 1
\subsubsection{Overlaps and Connections}
d149 1
a149 3
In some cases it is possible to reach the same Fields by different
routes.  These duplicated Fields may be treated as identical and no
benefit accrues from having the same Field more than once.
d151 7
a157 5
\begin{example}
Social World \imply Ethnology \imply Elves \imply Elves in the
Baronies, is the same as Social World \imply Ethnology \imply The
Baronies \imply Elves in the Baronies.
\end{example}
d159 5
a163 1
\subsubsection{Sage Status}
d165 1
a165 6
Philosophers of Rank 10 are often referred to as Sages.  Once a
Philosopher has achieved Rank 10, and Sage status, they may not Rank
their Profession further, but may acquire new Realms and Fields.  Each
new Realm costs 6000 ep, and requires 50 days of study, and each Point
used to purchase new fields costs 700 ep, and requires 7 days of
study.
d167 7
a173 4
\begin{example}
To learn a new Major Field costs 3 points, therefore it costs 2100 ep  and
requires 21 days of study.
\end{example}
d175 1
a175 1
\subsection{Realms and Fields}
