\subsection{Languages}

Philosophers gain a reduction in the Experience Points costs to learn
languages.  These benefits are in addition to any other reductions
available to the character.

\subsubsection{Speaking}

Philosophers may learn to speak languages at 75\% of the normal
Experience Point cost, provided that the Rank being gained in the
language is not greater than their Rank in Philosopher.

\subsubsection{Literacy}
d256 23
a278 162
Philosophers may become literate in any languages that they know, at
50\% of the normal Experience Point cost.

\subsection{Questions}

Philosophers may attempt to answer questions put to them, that they do
not already know the answers to.  These questions may be posed by
themselves, or by other characters.  The chance of successfully
answering a question (within the limitations of the knowledge
available) depends on the difficulty of the question and the relevant
Realms and Fields of the Philosopher.  What is very difficult for
someone with only a passing knowledge of the requisite field may be
very easy for someone who has made an in-depth study of that field.

\subsubsection{Difficulty}

Questions that may be answered by a Philosopher fall into one of five
categories; Very Easy, Easy, Standard, Hard, Very Hard.  The first
step in determining the difficulty of answering the question, is for
the GM to determine what area of knowledge and what exact level of
expertise would the question be Standard for.

A Standard question is one of average difficulty, relative to a given
Field, as determined by the GM.  They usually deal with a reasonably
large sub-set of the knowledge of the Field.

\begin{example}
The question ``Where do Fire Giants mostly live?''  is to the Major
Field ``Ethnology'' of the Social World whereas ``How are furs used in
Carzalan Heraldry?'' is Standard to the Sub-Field ``Carzalan
Heraldry'', of Minor Field ``Heraldry of Baronies'', of the Major
Field ``Heraldry and Genealogy'', of the Social World.
\end{example}

If the Philosopher possesses the Field for which the question is
Standard, but has no more in-depth knowledge applicable to the
question, the difficulty is Standard.  For each Child Field that the
Philosopher has, that the GM determines is relevant, the difficulty
decreases by one step: Standard \imply Easy \imply Very Easy.

\begin{example}
The question ``Where do Fire Giants mostly live?'' is Standard to
the Major Field ``Ethnology'' of the Social World.  As the Philosopher
attempting to answer the question has the Minor Field ``Giants'' of
the Major Field ``Ethnology'', the question becomes easy.  The
Philosopher also has the Sub-Field ``Giants in the Baronies'', but the
GM rules that this very specific information will not help shed light
on where Fire Giants as a group mostly live, and thus it will not help
with the question.
\end{example}

If the Philosopher does not possess the Field for which the question
is Standard, but possesses the Parent of that Field, the difficulty
increases by one step: Standard \imply Hard.  If the Philosopher only
possesses the Parent's Parent, the difficulty increases another step:
Hard \imply Very Hard.  A Philosopher may not answer a question more
than 2 steps removed from the relevant knowledge they possess.

\begin{example}
The question ``How are furs used in Carzalan Heraldry?'' is Standard
to the Sub-Field ``Carzalan Heraldry''.  As the Philosopher attempting
the question does not have that Sub-Field, or even its Parent the
Minor Field ``Heraldry in the Baronies'', but does have the Parent's
Parent Major Field ``Heraldry \& Genealogy'', the difficulty of
answering the question is increased two step to Very Hard.  If the
Philosopher did not know that Major Field, they would be unable to
answer the question at all.
\end{example}

If the Philosopher does not possess the Realm to which the question
belongs, they may not attempt to answer it, unless the question is
Standard at Realm level, in which case the Philosopher may attempt it
as a Hard question.  In some few cases a question may belong to more
than one Realm.

\subsubsection{Answers}

To achieve an answer to a question a Philosopher must undertake a
course of study.  The length of the study period is dependent on
experience, the difficulty of the question, and luck.  A Philosopher
begins their course of study with 0\% (plus a bonus for their
experience and the difficulty of the question) of the course complete.
For each study period (the length of which is determined by
difficulty), D10\% is added to the completeness of the study.  When
completeness reaches 100\%, the Philosopher has found an answer to the
question.  The bonus, and length of study period is determined as
follows:

\bigskip

{\fontsize{7}{8pt}\selectfont
\begin{tabular}{lcl}
\textbf{Difficulty} & \textbf{Bonus / Rank} & \textbf{Period} \\
Very Easy		& 8\%		& 5 minutes \\
Easy			& 6\%		& 10 minutes \\
Standard		& 4\%		& 15 minutes \\
Hard			& 2\%		& 2 hours \\
Very Hard		& 1\%		& 5 hours \\
\end{tabular}}
\smallskip

The GM should keep track of how far through their study the
Philosopher is, and it is the GM that makes the D10 rolls, keeping the
results secret from the player.  If the Philosopher wants to know how
far along they are, the GM may inform them in very general terms:
``About half way'', ``mostly complete''.

\begin{example}
A Rank 5 Philosopher is attempting to answer the question ``Where
do Fire Giants mostly live?''. it is of Standard difficulty for them.
When they begin, their course of study is 0\% + (4\% \x 5)
\imply 20\% complete.  Every 15 minutes that they spend studying the
GM rolls D10 and adds that number to the completeness. A while later
the player asks the GM how far through they are.  The GM consults their
running total: 63\%, and answers ``Maybe over half way?''
\end{example}

A Philosopher may, at any time, terminate an incomplete course of
study and attempt to answer the question.  Their accuracy will be
adversely affected however.

It is also possible that some questions (as determined by the GM) are
simply unanswerable.  If this is the case, upon completing their
course of study, the Philosopher will be aware (and convinced) of this
fact.

Even though Philosophers keep notes during their course of study, an
extended interruption may prove a setback.  If a Philosopher ceases a
course of study but resumes it within Rank weeks there are no adverse
effects.  If the interruption is longer than this then half of the
percentage amount that they had achieved, above the base amount for
their Rank and the difficulty of the question, is lost.

\subsubsection{Libraries}

To study to answer questions a Philosopher must have access to one or
more libraries.  A Philosopher may study any particular question at a
library for a number of days equal to the library's rating.  Once a
Philosopher has exhausted the possibilities of a library they must
either find another and continue their study or attempt to answer the
question anyway.  A day of study is 10 hours, and is full-time work.

\subsubsection{Accuracy}

Once the Philosopher has completed their study, (or has not completed
it, but is attempting to answer the question anyway), the GM must
determine the accuracy of the answer.  This accuracy is based on the
difficulty of the question, the experience of the Philosopher, and the
amount of study unfinished, if any.  The accuracy is calculated as
follows:

\smallskip

{\fontsize{7pt}{8}\selectfont
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
 & \textbf{Base} & \textbf{Per} & \\
\textbf{Difficulty} & \textbf{Chance} & \textbf{Rank} & \textbf{Reduct} \\
Very Easy	& 100\%		& +2\%	& -1\% \\
Easy		& 80\%		& +3\%	& -1\% \\
Standard	& 75\%		& +4\%	& -2\% \\
Hard		& 70\%		& +3\%	& -2\% \\
Very Hard	& 60\%		& +3\%	& -3\% \\
a279 4
\smallskip

*The Base Chance is reduced by the Percentage shown for each percent
of study left incomplete.
a280 19
The Base Chance may also be reduced by the GM if they feel that the
Philosopher's sources are particularly inaccurate.  GMs should be
cautious in applying this modifier, and should use it only in unusual
cases.

\subsubsection{Final Result}

If the question is of a Yes/No nature, the accuracy is the chance that
the Philosopher will arrive at the correct answer.  If the question is
more open, the accuracy is the amount of relevant information that the
Philosopher will come up with.

\begin{example}
A Philosopher has an 85\% accuracy with the question ``Can Dryads
use magic?''. This represents their chance of arriving at the answer
``Yes''.  A Philosopher is asked ``How are furs used in Carzalan Heraldry?''
and achieves a result of 115\%, which means they can answer question
and more besides (about 15\% more than the Questioner wanted to know).
\end{example}
